{{Politics of Oklahoma}}
'''Chris Benge''' is a Republican politician from Oklahoma. Benge currently serves in the [[Oklahoma House of Representatives]] as the [[Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], a position he took over after [[Lance Cargill]] resigned in January 2008. <ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=20080204_1__OKLAH26268 "House Republicans choose Benge to become speaker designate"], [http://www.tulsaworld.com Tulsa World]. Retrieved on May 7, 2009. </ref><ref> [http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=20080128_1__OKLAH32863 "House Speaker Lance Cargill steps down after not paying taxes"], [http://www.tulsaworld.com Tulsa World]. Retrieved on May 7, 2009. </ref>

Benge was first elected to the House of Representatives in 1998. Due to term limits placed on him by the [[Oklahoma Constitution]], his final term will end in January, 2011.

A native Tulsan, he currently resides in the community of Berryhill with his wife Allison and their two children, Garrett and Hayden. <ref> [http://www.okhouse.gov/Members/HouseOrg.aspx Oklahoma House Members 2008], [http://www.okhouse.gov Oklahoma House of Representatives]. Retrieved on May 7, 2009. </ref>

==Early life and career==
Benge was born and raised in southwest Tulsa. He graduated from Webster High School in 1980 and graduated from Oklahoma State University with a degree in business. Benge has managed a business, Benge Painting Company from 1981 to 1997. <ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=23614 Chris Benge Complete Bio], [http://www.votesmart.org VoteSmart.org]. Retrieved on May 7, 2009. </ref>

==Organizations==
*Southwest Tulsa Chamber of Commerce, 1999-present
*Southwest Sertoma Club, 1999-present
*American Legislative Exchange Council
*Berryhill Drug Education Council
*Going to Bat for Kids, Mentoring Program
*View Across Baptist Church
*Westside Coalition for Youth. 

==District==
House District 68 encompasses southwest Tulsa and a portion of Tulsa County outside of the city. It also includes a small portion of Creek County. The district is a mix of urban Tulsa neighborhoods and Tulsa suburbs. <ref> [http://www.okhouse.gov/Research/HouseDistricts.aspx "House Districts, Congressional and Other Maps"], [http://www.okhouse.gov Oklahoma House of Representatives]. Retrieved on May 7, 2009. </ref>

